This article is about an executive order issued by President Donald Trump on April 28, 2020, regarding the impact of the COVID-19 pandemic on the meat and poultry industry in the United States. The order acknowledges the disruption caused by the virus and the necessary mitigation measures, such as social distancing, which have affected the economy and critical infrastructure. The order emphasizes the importance of maintaining the supply of protein for Americans and addresses the closure of processing facilities due to COVID-19 outbreaks among workers. It states that such closures can have a significant impact on the food supply chain and undermine critical infrastructure. The Secretary of Agriculture is delegated the authority to ensure that meat and poultry processors continue operations in line with the guidance issued by the CDC and OSHA. The order also grants the Secretary of Agriculture the authority to determine priorities and allocate necessary resources to ensure the continued supply of meat and poultry. The order is implemented in accordance with applicable law and subject to the availability of appropriations.